summary: I am an experienced researcher in the field of molecular biology and plant physiology. During my lab work I have shown to be a hard-working person with ability to obtain results under pressure, both independent and as a part of a team.  Working in the lab environment taught me also to work on multiple projects simultaneously while meeting tight deadlines and still staying focused on results.  Being ambitious pushes me to improve and develop new skills. As for my personal skills, next to excellent organizational talent, I posses good communicative abilities, both in English and Polish. Furthermore, I can be characterized as a highly motivated quick-learner what makes me a great addition to any team.

In my PhD project I was to (i) functionally identify important amino acid residues using TT12 as a model for plant MATE family, (ii) functionally characterise two novel MATE transporters in Lupinus albus implicated in citrate and isoflavonoids transport and (iii) identify novel flavonoid transporters within the 56 members of the Arabidopsis MATE family. 

Main technical skills gained and improved during that time:

Molecular techniques: All standard (DNA/RNA) techniques including genomic DNA and RNA isolation from different organisms and tissues; PCR techniques (sqRT-PCR, PCR-based cDNA identification/isolation); gene cloning, vector/plasmid construction for different  expression systems; recombination-based cloning (Gateway, Invitrogen); site-directed mutagensis; use of Saccharomyces cerevisiae as a model organism.

Biochemical techniques: Isolation of intact subcellular fractions, e.g. protoplasts, vacuoles etc.; isolation of membrane vesicles; transmembrane transport experiments with intact organelles, vesicles using filtration techniques and pH sensitive dye; reporter-gene systems (glucoronidase, all fluorescent proteins); subcellular localisation techniques.

Plant technques: Arabidopsis techniques: reverse and forward genetics, isolation, verification and characterisation of mutants; plant transformation; gene overexpression; promoter analysis; expression analysis (RNA, sq-PCR). Transient gene expression in Nicotiana benthamiana.

Analytical and microscope tools: UV/Vis- and fluorescence microscopy; liquid scintillation counters; plate readers (e.g. Fusion, Packard); bright-field, epifluorescence and laser scanning confocal microscopy.

A combination of metabolic and transcript profiling and correlation analysis have been utilized on systematically perturbed systems to identify candidate genes for modifying important metabolite contents within a system biology. When applying pair-wise transcript analysis, an important number of pairs exhibited significant correlations. Whilst several of these correlations were expected, or predictable, most of them were novel and included several strong correlations between transcripts and nutritionally important metabolites.
My task was to test the function of the homologue genes (e.g. Anthranilate phosphoribosyl-transferase, Caffeoyl-CoA methyltransferase) in transgenic antisense Arabidopsis thaliana plants. For plants characterisation following techniques have been performed: Northern blot, microarray techniques, enzyme assays, HPLC, GC-MS. 
I have also joined other experiments carried out within the group and performed conventional plant molecular biology experiments, feeding experiments and general plant handling.
